  "recommendation": "flag-for-review",
  "calibration_note": "MEASUREMENT GAP, NOT A DECLINE — and note the trigger is weaker than the scan implies. Kimberly-Clark has never been individually assessed; the published 60.9 is a bulk-import placeholder with a near-flat 3.5. The -10.9 gap is largely that arithmetic difference. On the trigger itself: the $2.25 million 401(k) excessive-fee settlement is real, but it was finally approved in July 2025, and the July 2026 item the scan surfaced is a subsequent procedural step rather than a new finding. A recordkeeping-fee settlement covering roughly 25,000 participants at about 15 percent of estimated maximum losses is a genuine but minor governance failure — it is one data point in a forty-part assessment, not the assessment. Kimberly-Clark's actual conduct record in the window is mixed-to-positive: sustained sanitation and menstrual-health access programmes against a workforce reduction at the company it is acquiring. Recommendation is flag-for-review for cohort calibration, not a conduct-based downgrade.",
